article.description:
Tangela Smith scored 17 points as the
Charlotte Sting beat the Indiana Fever 75-65 on Saturday to post
consecutive wins for the first time this season.
article.headline: Smith, Sting give Fever chills, win second straight
article.linkText: Smith, Sting give Fever chills, win second straight
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- After a disastrous first half of the
season, the Charlotte Sting have taken on a different look.

Tangela Smith scored 17 points as the Sting beat the Indiana
Fever 75-65 on Saturday to post consecutive wins for the first time
this season.

Tammy Sutton-Brown added 13 points and nine rebounds and Kelly
Mazzante scored 10 points for the Sting (5-16), who last won two
straight last Aug. 23-25.

"It makes basketball fun -- and sleep a lot better too,"
Sutton-Brown said. "We decided after the All-Star break it would
be a new season. Right now we're 2-0 and that sounds a lot better
than 5-and-whatever.

"It feels better, the mood is good, but these last two games
we've just played well together."

The Sting, who have won only 11 games in two seasons, appeared
in danger of letting a 21-point third-quarter lead slip away when
Tan White's layup with 6:59 left made it 58-54. But Smith had a
3-point play and Mazzante hit a 3-pointer in a 10-2 run to give the
Sting a 68-56 lead with 3:44 left.

Charlotte, which committed a season-low eight turnovers, was not
threatened again.

"We understand now how to match other teams' intensity," Sting
coach Muggsy Bogues said. "We can't expect that after we get up by
a nice margin, they're not going to keep coming. We're getting a
lot of communication out there."

Tamika Catchings and Tamika Whitmore had 17 points apiece for
the Fever (13-8), who shot 32 percent and lost for the second time
in three meetings with the Sting. Third-place Indiana remained 1½
games behind first-place Connecticut in the Eastern Conference.

"We probably took too many outside shots and didn't get the
ball inside enough," Fever coach Brian Winters said. "Charlotte
has improved a lot and they seem to match up with us pretty well.
Tangela Smith has played very well as of late. I don't want to play
them too many more times."

Smith, who scored 25 points in Charlotte's 81-65 win over San
Antonio on Friday night, hit back-to-back 3s in a 17-2 run to close
the first half that gave the Sting a 39-24 lead.

Helen Darling's jumper early in the third quarter made it 47-26.

"We were waiting for a day like this," Bogues said. "We've
been trying hard to turn this thing around."

Catchings, who missed Wednesday's All-Star game with tendinitis
in her left Achilles', started and made 6-of-11 shots and grabbed
seven rebounds. But she got little help, as fellow starters
Whitmore, Ebony Hoffman, Anna DeForge and Tully Bevilaqua combined
to shoot 7-for-35 in Indiana's third loss in four games.

"The injury is fine," Catchings said. "Of course during the
game it started to swell, but that is to be expected. I feel as
time progresses it will become less of a factor."
